<LayerPage
  eyebrow="Core · 03 inference"
  layerTag="The living core · inference"
  title="Private inference, on hardware you own."
  lede="The moment the model actually works. Every prompt and response is processed locally, on infrastructure under your control, with nothing sent to an external API — this is the step where shadow AI stops being a policy problem and becomes architecturally impossible."
  seoTitle={seoTitle}
  seoDescription={seoDescription}
  points={points}
  standards={standards}
>
  <!-- Why local inference is the whole point -->
  <section class="bg-white dark:bg-black border-b border-zinc-200 dark:border-zinc-800">
    <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-6 lg:px-8 py-20">
      <p class="text-xs font-mono uppercase tracking-widest text-olive-600 dark:text-olive-400 mb-4">Why this step is the whole point</p>
      <h2 class="text-3xl md:text-4xl font-bold tracking-tight text-zinc-900 dark:text-white mb-6">
        The data leaves at exactly one moment — so we removed it.
      </h2>
      <div class="space-y-5 text-lg text-zinc-700 dark:text-zinc-300 leading-relaxed">
        <p>
          In a conventional setup, your data is private right up until the instant it is sent to
          a model to be answered. That single moment of egress is where sovereignty is lost — and
          it is the moment most "private AI" quietly keeps. Inference is the step where we close
          it: the model answers <strong>where the data already is</strong>.
        </p>
        <p>
          Solve it here and everything downstream follows. There is no public model to leak to,
          no third party to trust with the prompt, and no contract clause standing in for a
          guarantee. The boundary holds because the computation never crossed it.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

